  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT308-kilavi">varaiviṭaik kiḻattiyai vaṉcol colli vaṟpuṟuttiyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Encouraging HER, speaking strong words at the time of
          marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT308">
          <l> cōlai vāḻaic curinukum piṉaiya</l>
          <l> vaṇaṅkuṭai yaruntalai nīvaliṉ mataṉaḻintu</l>
          <l> mayaṅkutuya ruṟṟa maiyal vēḻa</l>
          <l> muyaṅkuyir maṭappiṭi yulaipuṟan taivara</l>
          <l> vāmiḻi cilampi ṉaritukaṇ paṭukku</l>
          <l> māmalai nāṭaṉ kēṇmai</l>
          <l> kāman taruvatōr kaitāḻn taṉṟē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Bringing only <note place="foot"> 	Is it possible to take <term xml:lang="ta"> ōr </term> in this way as an adverb?    </note> desire [now] it has lowered [its] hand, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> kai tāḻntaṉṟu </term> has presumably to be taken in a transferred sense, namely the giving hand as a metaphor for active attachment.  </note></l>
          <l>the friendship of the man from the land of big mountains,</l>
          <l rend="indent">where the proud elephant bull rarely <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">	aritu </term> must be taken as an adverb here. </note> closes [his] eyes,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">on the mountain slope where the water is falling,</l>
          <l rend="indent8">beset by confusing misery</l>
          <l rend="indent2">after [his] rutting vigour has perished from a curved leaf</l>
          <l rend="indent8">of the banana tree</l>
          <l rend="indent3">in the woods stroking [his] desperately tormented, difficult head,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">while the youthful female with weakened breath <note place="foot"> What is expressed by <term xml:lang="ta"> uyaṅku uyir </term>? Is she exhausted after copulation?    </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent8">rubs [his] ruined back. <note place="foot">The subtle syntax as well as the intention of lines 1-4 are fairly hard to understand. Is the point of the whole an erotic transfer? Like the elephant which is utterly exhausted after excessive sexual activity, HE is afterwards good for nothing? T.V.G. explains it completely different, namely as one (the clearest) occurrence of a rare topos, namely that elephants are in danger of loosing their strength upon the contact or consummation of tender banana leaves. Here the bull is weakened so much that he is falling asleep, which is said to be rare with elephants.   </note></l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="6+7b" resp="#TVG">
            <l>The friendship ... resulted in the singular habit of inducing desire.<note place="foot"> Thus the interpretation of T.V.G. who thinks the point SHE wants to bring home to the confidante is the sexual nature of HER attachment to HIM. A rendering of <term xml:lang="ta"> tāḻntaṉṟu </term> by "it resulted" is not encouraged by the semantics of this root, which is usually applied to fruits or branches hanging down, sometimes falling down, from a tree.    </note> </l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
